But a much bigger challenge to the state's policy against hardened structures along the coast could be brewing - and not just because the Riggings ruling might be unique to that situation.

When the General Assembly reconvenes in Raleigh Jan. 28, supporters of a plan to allow beach communities to build terminal groins near unstable inlets are promising a renewed push.

The idea isn't new. It was first floated two years ago. But it never garnered enough support from both chambers of the legislature to gain any traction in the face of opposition by then-Gov. Mike Easley.

This year, however, things could be different.

Proponents have broadened the bills' backers beyond Figure Eight Island to remove the stigma of a rich, private island looking to protect million-dollar homes.

Now, towns from the Outer Banks to Brunswick County intend to press their representatives to get the state's ban softened to make exceptions for erosion around the volatile inlets.

Their argument goes something like this: The state's long-standing ban on sea walls and jetties shouldn't be changed. But inlets are special situations that require special tools to protect people and property, since traditional options such as beach nourishment have proven ineffective.

That preferred solution would be a terminal groin - a low-slung wall adjacent to an inlet that would trap enough sand to stabilize the immediate beach area. Eventually it would be buried and let excess sand by.

"This is not like other structures people are worried about," said Caswell Beach Mayor Harry Simmons, who also is the executive director of the N.C. Beach, Inlet and Waterway Association.

"This is a sediment-management tool, not an armoring device. And since we already have a different set of rules for building around inlets, why don't we have a different set of tools in our toolbox to deal with erosion there?"

But Jim Stephenson, coastal policy analyst with the N.C. Coastal Federation, said the only thing that's changed this time around is the amount of money the bill's proponents have to lobby legislators.

He said the state is already moving to expand its inlet-hazard areas to allow them to include all areas influenced by the volatile channels so that future development doesn't face the same problems current homes do.

But he maintains that hardened structures simply move the erosion problem to someplace else along the beachfront.

He also hinted that the federation may appeal the ruling allowing The Riggings to keep its sandbags if state regulators decide not to.

But even Judge Jay Hockenbury said his ruling might be specific to The Riggings and not very applicable to the roughly 150 other sandbag structures along the coast that state regulators have said need to come out.

The condos are squeezed between federally protected coquina rock and a state-built rock revetment, effectively starving The Riggings of sand and a stable beach.

