Radioactive isotopes such as iodine 131, cesium 137 and strontium 90 are passed on to people through cowâ€™s milk, she said. â€œThey come out of the stack and fall on the ground. They permeate the water and are eaten in food.â€

<http://michiganmessenger.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/cows-technically-nina.jpg>
Michigan cow (Photo: Technically Nina via Flickr.com)

Children are particularly vulnerable to this radiation, she said. â€œIt doesnâ€™t take 40 years to get leukemia if you are a kid.â€

