In March 2000, the agency seemed on the verge of proposing stricter federal controls. Staff in the solid-waste office wrote a draft determination essentially classifying coal ash as â€œcontingent hazardous wasteâ€ â€” a hybrid designation. In the <http://www.publicintegrity.org/assets/pdf/CoalAsh-Doc7.pdf>91-page document, which the Center for Public Integrity obtained from the White Houseâ€™s Office of Management and Budget, the agency proposed to regulate the dumping of coal ash in ponds, landfills, and mine pits with â€œtailoredâ€ national standards. If power companies were to abide by them, the document states, â€œwastes would remain non-hazardous.â€ If not, the coal ash would be classified as â€œhazardous.â€ In effect, agency officials were straddling the regulatory line to encourage better management. The draft determination states, in part, that the tailored regulations are the best solution in light of â€œthe evidence of actual and potential damage to human health or the environment from these wastes, the sheer volume of wastesâ€¦ [and] the significant number of facilities that do not currently have basic controls in placeâ€¦â€

Browner, who declined to comment for this article, sent the draft determination, dated March 5, 2000, to the OMB for review, which set off a frenzy of lobbying by the utility industry. The White House was inundated with letters from trade organizations such as the Edison Electric Institute and the Utility Solid Waste Activities Group (USWAG) â€” the industryâ€™s voice on coal-ash disposal â€” criticizing the draft. One letter, signed by then-USWAG chairman Fred McGuire and 13 other industry representatives, warned that â€œthe high costs of [hazardous] regulationâ€¦ will ultimately be shared nationwide by employees, taxpayers, ratepayers, investors, and customers.â€ Another letter, from the presidents of 16 energy companies, blasted the proposal as â€œover-regulation and an unwarranted intrusion into an area of primary state responsibility.â€

