Matthew Hale, director of the EPAâ€™s solid-waste office, declined requests to be interviewed, as did Richard Kinch, the manager who has overseen the coal ash research and policy work. In answer to written questions, the EPAâ€™s press office provided a five-page statement which states that, â€œa range of issues came up during administrative review of EPAâ€™s draft determination on coal combustion residue, including cost.â€ The final regulatory determination, the EPA says, â€œreflected the Agencyâ€™s judgment as to the most appropriate regulatory approach.â€

Timothy Fields, who ran the EPAâ€™s Office of Solid Waste and Emergency Response in 2000, remembers the agencyâ€™s final determination having more to do with internal discussions between top officials at the EPA, OMB, and White House Council on Environmental Quality than any outside pressure. Throughout the OMB review, he says, it became apparent that the EPA lacked not only the administrative record to justify its draft, but also the needed inter-agency backing.

â€œThere was some consensus that the draft determination was going too far and the problems of coal ash could be dealt with in another way. This wasnâ€™t the way to do it,â€ says John Spotila, Clintonâ€™s administrator in OMBâ€™s Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs in 2000.

