The EPA, in its statement, says that voluntary plans have perks â€” â€œthey can often be implemented more quickly than new regulationsâ€ â€” but that â€œit has not determined that it is considering this voluntary plan in lieu of [non-hazardous] regulation.â€

<http://www.publicintegrity.org/assets/img/Ash6.JPG>An 80-foot-high containment wall for a coal-ash storage pond blends into the landscape near the Colstrip plant. Photo by Kristen Lombardi.Industry representatives still argue that the states have adequate regulations. This time, their claims seem bolstered by a 2006 energy department survey examining newly constructed ponds and landfills. The report found a trend toward more modern controls â€” ponds with monitoring wells grew by 20 percent, for instance â€” as well as more stringent state regulations.

