Roewer maintains that most cases involving coal-ash contamination stem from old practices no longer in vogue. â€œWhen we have seen damage cases, the utilities have moved to address the problem and clean up the sites,â€ he says, citing the 15 cases on the EPAâ€™s damages list for which the agency has confirmed corrective action, such as laying new liners.

