Back in Colstrip, the situation seems to undermine the industryâ€™s claims. Montana lawmakers have actually loosened key protections preventing coal-ash contamination â€” first, by exempting on-site disposal from the stateâ€™s solid-waste regulations; second, by gutting a law meant to manage the citing of coal-fired power plants. Both acts have left the stateâ€™s Department of Environmental Quality with little authority over this waste.

As a result, Colstrip station â€” a â€œlegacyâ€ plant built when those regulations were still in effect â€“ is now the only plant whose coal ash the state oversees. But its widespread plumes of ash have laid bare the fact that the power companies long operated their ponds as if state regulatory agency rules didnâ€™t apply. The plantâ€™s January 1976 permit mandates that the ponds act as a â€œclosed-loop systemâ€ that â€œdoes not discharge effluents from the plant downstream or into other waters.â€ Any seepage, it states, â€œis not anticipated to impair the quality of [area] groundwater.â€ Under the permit, state regulators can fine the companies $10,000 a day for tarnishing water. Yet, Ring, the Montana regulator, confirms, â€œThat has never happened.â€

