11. SOLAR POWER: Utility breaks ground on first Sunshine State PV project(02/26/2009)

Michael Burnham, E&E senior reporter

Florida Power & Light Co. broke ground today on a 25-megawatt solar power plant, the Sunshine State's first commerical-scale photovoltaic array.

When completed later this year, the project will consist of 90,000 photovoltaic panels on 180 acres located halfway between Tampa Bay and Lake Okeechobee. Florida Power & Light, a subsidiary of FPL Group Inc. (NYSE: FPL), will own and operate the DeSoto County project.

"Solar power will help promote a new clean-energy economy in Florida, reduce our dependence on fossil fuels and address climate change through the production of emissions-free energy," FPL Group President Jim Robo said of the $173 million project, which will generate enough electricity for roughly 3,000 homes.

The DeSoto project is one of three solar power installations FPL has in the pipeline.

In December, the Miami-based utility broke ground on a 75 MW solar-thermal array adjacent to the company's combined-cycle power plant in Martin County, east of Lake Okeechobee. The array of 180,000 mirrors, slated for completion next year, will concentrate sunlight on water to produce steam that will offset the natural gas that is currently used in the adjacent combined-cycle plant.

Florida Power & Light plans to break ground on the third project -- a 10 MW array of PV panels -- in Cape Canaveral later this year.

The three solar projects will have the capacity to produce 110 MW and cost roughly $700 million to build, collectively. The utility will pass the cost along to ratepayers over 25 years, which means the typical residential customer will see a 31-cent increase in his monthly utility bill, explained Jackie Anderson, a Florida Power & Light spokeswoman.

A draft study conducted by Navigant Consulting for the Florida Public Service Commission estimated that Florida could support 89,000 MW of solar photovoltaic panels on rooftops and the ground. The state could support another 380 MW of hybrid solar-thermal/combined-cycle power plants.

Florida Gov. Charlie Crist (R) has called for the state to get 20 percent of its electricity from the sun and other renewable resources by 2020. The Florida Public Service Commission is developing a draft renewable portfolio standard for the Legislature to consider later this year.


